{"title_page": "1945 in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|USA-related events during the year of 1945}}\n{{Yearbox US|1945}}\n\nEvents from the year '''1945 in the United States'''. [[World War II]] ended during this year following the surrender of [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] in May and that of [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] in September.\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Incumbents ==\n=== [[Federal government of the United States|Federal Government]] ===\n* [[President of the United States|President]]: [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[New York (state)|New York]]) (until April 12), [[Harry S. Truman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Missouri]]) (starting April 12)\n* [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]:\n** until January 20: [[Henry A. Wallace]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Iowa]])\n** January 20\u2013April 12: [[Harry S. Truman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Missouri]])\n** starting April 12: ''vacant''\n* [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]]: [[Harlan F. Stone]] ([[New York (state)|New York]])\n* [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]]: [[Sam Rayburn]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Texas]])\n* [[Senate Majority Leader]]: [[Alben W. Barkley]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Kentucky]])\n* [[United States Congress|Congress]]: [[78th United States Congress|78th]] (until January 3), [[79th United States Congress|79th]] (starting January 3)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! [[Governor (United States)|Governor]]s and [[Lieutenant governor (United States)|Lieutenant Governor]]s\n|-\n|\n=== Governors ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Governor of Alabama]]: [[Chauncey Sparks]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Arizona]]: [[Sidney Preston Osborn]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Arkansas]]: [[Homer Martin Adkins]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 9), [[Benjamin Travis Laney]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 9)\n* [[Governor of California]]: [[Earl Warren]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Colorado]]: [[John Charles Vivian]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Connecticut]]: [[Raymond E. Baldwin]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Delaware]]: [[Walter W. Bacon]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Florida]]: [[Spessard Holland]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 2), [[Millard F. Caldwell]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 2)\n* [[Governor of Georgia]]: [[Ellis Arnall]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Idaho]]: \n** until January 1: [[C. A. Bottolfsen]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n** January 1-November 17: [[Charles C. Gossett]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n** starting November 17: [[Arnold Williams (American politician)|Arnold Williams]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Governor of Illinois]]: [[Dwight H. Green]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Indiana]]: [[Henry F. Schricker]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 8), [[Ralph F. Gates]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 8) \n* [[Governor of Iowa]]: [[Bourke B. Hickenlooper]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 11), [[Robert D. Blue]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 11)\n* [[Governor of Kansas]]: [[Andrew F. Schoeppel]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Kentucky]]: [[Simeon S. Willis]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Louisiana]]: [[Jimmie H. Davis]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Maine]]: [[Sumner Sewall]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 3), [[Horace A. Hildreth]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 3)\n* [[Governor of Maryland]]: [[Herbert R. O'Conor]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Massachusetts]]: [[Leverett Saltonstall]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 3), [[Maurice J. Tobin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 3)\n* [[Governor of Michigan]]: [[Harry Kelly (politician)|Harry Kelly]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Minnesota]]: [[Edward John Thye]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Mississippi]]: [[Thomas L. Bailey]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Missouri]]: [[Forrest C. Donnell]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 8), [[Phil M. Donnelly]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 8)\n* [[Governor of Montana]]: [[Sam C. Ford]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Nebraska]]: [[Dwight Griswold]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Nevada]]: [[Edward P. Carville]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until July 24), [[Vail M. Pittman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting July 24)\n* [[Governor of New Hampshire]]: [[Robert O. Blood]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 4), [[Charles M. Dale]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 4)\n* [[Governor of New Jersey]]: [[Walter Evans Edge]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of New Mexico]]: [[John J. Dempsey]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of New York]]: [[Thomas Dewey]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of North Carolina]]: [[J. Melville Broughton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 4), [[R. Gregg Cherry]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 4)\n* [[Governor of North Dakota]]: [[John Moses (American politician)|John Moses]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 4), [[Fred George Aandahl|Fred G. Aandahl]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 4)\n* [[Governor of Ohio]]: [[John W. Bricker]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 8), [[Frank J. Lausche]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 8)\n* [[Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[Robert S. Kerr]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Oregon]]: [[Earl Snell]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[Edward Martin (Pennsylvania politician)|Edward Martin]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Rhode Island]]: [[J. Howard McGrath]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until October 6), [[John Orlando Pastore]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting October 6)\n* [[Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Olin D. Johnston]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 2), [[Ransome Judson Williams]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 2)\n* [[Governor of South Dakota]]: [[Merrill Q. Sharpe]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Tennessee]]: [[Prentice Cooper]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 16), [[Jim Nance McCord]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 16)\n* [[Governor of Texas]]: [[Coke R. Stevenson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Utah]]: [[Herbert B. Maw]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Vermont]]: [[William Henry Wills (politician)|William H. Wills]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 4), [[Mortimer R. Proctor]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 4)\n* [[Governor of Virginia]]: [[Colgate Darden]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Washington]]: [[Arthur B. Langlie]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 8), [[Monrad C. Wallgren]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 8)\n* [[Governor of West Virginia]]: [[Matthew M. Neely]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 15), [[Clarence W. Meadows]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 15)\n* [[Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Walter S. Goodland]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Wyoming]]: [[Lester C. Hunt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n}}\n\n=== Lieutenant Governors ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]: [[Leven H. Ellis]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Arkansas]]: [[James Lavesque Shaver]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])  \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of California]]: [[Frederick F. Houser]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Colorado]]: [[William Eugene Higby]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut]]: [[William L. Hadden]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until month and day unknown), [[Charles Wilbert Snow]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Delaware]]: [[Isaac J. MacCollum]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 16), [[Elbert N. Carvel]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 16)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Idaho]]: \n** until January 1: [[Edwin Nelson (politician)|Edwin Nelson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n** January 1-November 17: [[Arnold Williams (American politician)|Arnold Williams]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n** starting November 17: vacant\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Illinois]]: [[Hugh W. Cross]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Indiana]]: [[Charles M. Dawson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 8), [[Richard T. James (politician)|Richard T. James]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 8)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Iowa]]: [[Robert D. Blue]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 11), [[Kenneth A. Evans]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 11)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Kansas]]: [[Dodge City Daily Globe|Jess C. Denious, Sr.]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Kentucky]]: [[Kenneth H. Tuggle]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Louisiana]]: [[J. Emile Verret]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Massachusetts]]: [[Horace T. Cahill]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 3), vacant (starting January 3)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan]]: [[Eugene C. Keyes]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until month and day unknown), [[Vernon J. Brown]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Minnesota]]: [[Archie H. Miller]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 2), [[C. Elmer Anderson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 2)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]: [[Fielding L. Wright]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Missouri]]: vacant (until January 8), [[Walter Naylor Davis]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 8)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Montana]]: [[Ernest T. Eaton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nebraska]]: [[Roy W. Johnson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]: [[Vail M. Pittman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until July 24), vacant (starting July 24)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]: James B. Jones ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New York]]: [[Joe R. Hanley|Joseph R. Hanley]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Carolina]]: [[Reginald L. Harris]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 4), [[Lynton Y. Ballentine]]  ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 4)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Dakota]]: vacant (until January 4), [[Clarence P. Dahl]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 4)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Ohio]]: [[Paul M. Herbert]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 8), [[George D. Nye]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 8)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[James E. Berry]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[John C. Bell, Jr.]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Rhode Island]]: \n** until month and day unknown: vacant\n** month and day unknown: [[John O. Pastore]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n** starting month and day unknown: vacant\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Ransome Judson Williams]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 2), vacant (starting January 2)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Dakota]]: [[Albert C. Miller|A. C. Miller]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until month and day unknown), [[Sioux K. Grigsby]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Tennessee]]: Joseph H. Ballew ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until month and day unknown), Larry Morgan ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]: [[John Lee Smith]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]]: [[Mortimer R. Proctor]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 4), [[Lee E. Emerson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 4)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Virginia]]: [[William M. Tuck]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]]: [[Victor A. Meyers]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Oscar Rennebohm]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n}}\n|}\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n[[File:FDR in 1933.jpg|thumb|120px|upright|[[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], the [[President of the United States]], began his fourth term on January 20]]\n*January &ndash; [[United States Army|American troops]] cross the [[Siegfried Line]] into Belgium.\n* January 6 &ndash; Naval lieutenant [[George H. W. Bush]], future President of the United States, and future First Lady [[Barbara Bush|Barbara Pierce]] marry in [[Rye, New York]].\n* January 20 &ndash; [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] is inaugurated to an unprecedented fourth term as [[President of the United States]]. No president before, or since, reaches a third term in office.\n* January 30 &ndash; [[Raid at Cabanatuan]]: 121 American soldiers and 800 Filipino guerrillas free 813 American [[Prisoner of War|POWs]] from the Japanese-held camp at [[Cabanatuan City]], [[Philippines]].\n* January 31 &ndash; [[Eddie Slovik]] is executed by firing squad for [[desertion]], the first American soldier since the [[American Civil War]], and last to date to be executed for this offense.\n\n===February===\nhowdy folks it's dinner time. KFC\n[[File:Yalta Conference (Churchill, Roosevelt, Stalin) (B&W).jpg|thumb|right|120px|February 4\u201311: [[Yalta Conference]]]]\n* February 2 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Winston Churchill]] leave to meet with [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] leader [[Joseph Stalin]] at the [[Yalta Conference]].\n* February 3 &ndash; United States forces capture [[Manila]], [[Philippines]] from the [[Japanese Imperial Army]].\n* February 4 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] [[Winston Churchill]] and [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] leader [[Joseph Stalin]] begin the [[Yalta Conference]] (ends February 11).\n* February 7 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: General [[Douglas MacArthur]] returns to [[Manila]].\n* February 16 \n**Combined American and Filipino forces recapture the [[Bataan]] Peninsula.\n**American and Filipino ground forces land on [[Corregidor]] Island in the [[Philippines]].\n* February 19 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]] &ndash; [[Battle of Iwo Jima]]: About 30,000 [[United States Marine]]s land on [[Iwo Jima]].\n* February 23 \n**The American and Filipino troops enter [[Intramuros, Manila]].\n**The capital of the [[Philippines]], Manila, is liberated by combined American and Filipino ground troops.\n**[[Battle of Iwo Jima]]: A group of [[United States Marine]]s reach the top of [[Mount Suribachi]] on the island and are photographed raising the [[flag of the United States|American flag]]. The photo, ''[[Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima]]'' (taken by [[Joe Rosenthal]]), later wins a [[Pulitzer Prize]].\n\n===March===\n* March 1 &ndash; United States President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] gives what will be his last address to a joint session of Congress, reporting on the [[Yalta Conference]].\n* March 2 &ndash; Former Vice President [[Henry Agard Wallace]] starts his term of office as [[United States Secretary of Commerce|U.S. Secretary of Commerce]], serving under President Roosevelt.\n* March 3 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: United States and Filipino troops take [[Manila]], [[Philippines]].\n* March 7 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: American troops seize the bridge over the [[Rhine River]] at [[Remagen]], Germany and begin to cross.\n* March 15 &ndash; The [[17th Academy Awards]] ceremony is held, broadcast via radio for the first time. [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] goes to ''[[Going My Way]]''.\n* March 19 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: Off the coast of Japan, bombers hit the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Franklin|CV-13|6}}, killing about 800 of her crewmen and crippling the ship.\n* March 24 &ndash; The cartoon character [[Sylvester (Looney Tunes)|Sylvester the cat]] debuts in ''[[Life with Feathers]]''\n* March 29 &ndash; The \"Clash of Titans\" in basketball: [[George Mikan]] and [[Bob Kurland]] duel at [[Madison Square Garden (1925)|Madison Square Garden]] as [[Oklahoma State University|OSU]] defeats [[DePaul University|DePaul]] 52\u201344.\n\n===April===\n[[File:HarryTruman.jpg|thumb|right|120px|April 12: [[Harry S. Truman]] becomes President upon the death of [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]]]\n* April 1 &ndash; [[World War II|WWII]] &ndash; [[Battle of Okinawa]]: United States troops land on [[Okinawa]].\n* April 4 &ndash; WWII &ndash; American troops liberate their first Nazi concentration camp, [[Ohrdruf]] [[death camp]] in Germany.\n* April 7 &ndash; The only flight of the German ramming unit known as the [[Sonderkommando Elbe]] takes place, resulting in the loss of some 24 [[B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17]]s and [[B-24 Liberator|B-24]]s of the United States [[Eighth Air Force]].\n* April 12 &ndash; President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] dies suddenly at [[Warm Springs, Georgia]]; Vice President [[Harry S. Truman]] becomes the 33rd President.\n* April 18 &ndash; The American [[war correspondent]] [[Ernie Pyle]] is killed by Japanese [[machine gun]] fire on the island of [[Ie Shima]] off Okinawa.\n* April 19 &ndash; [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]'s ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]],'' a musical play based on [[Ferenc Moln\u00e1r]]'s ''[[Liliom]],'' opens on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] and becomes their second long-running stage classic.\n* April 25 \n**WWII &ndash; [[Elbe Day]]: United States and [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] troops link up at the [[Elbe River]], cutting Germany in two.\n**Founding negotiations for the [[United Nations]] begin in San Francisco.\n* April 27 &ndash; U.S. Ordnance troops find the coffins of 18th-century [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] kings [[Frederick Wilhelm I]] and [[Frederick the Great]], in addition to [[President of Germany|German President]] [[Paul Von Hindenburg]] and his wife.\n\n===May===\n* May 3 &ndash; Rocket scientist [[Wernher von Braun]] and 120 members of his team surrender to U.S. forces (later he became at the forefront and a pioneer of the U.S. space program).\n* May 5 \n**A Japanese [[Fu-Go balloon bomb]] kills five children and a grown woman, Elsie Mitchell, near [[Bly, Oregon]], when it explodes as they drag it from the woods. They are the only people killed by an enemy attack on the American mainland during World War II.\n**The [[US 11th Armored Division]] liberates the prisoners of [[Mauthausen concentration camp]], including [[Simon Wiesenthal]].\n**[[Ezra Pound]], the poet and author, is arrested by American soldiers in Italy for treason.\n* May 8 &ndash; [[Victory in Europe Day]]: The [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] accept Germany's unconditional surrender.\n* May 9 &ndash; [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]] is captured by the [[United States Army]]; Norway arrests the traitor [[Vidkun Quisling]].\n\n===June===\n===July===\n* July 8 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: President [[Harry S. Truman]] is informed that Japan will talk peace if it can retain the reign of the Emperor.<ref name=\"nuclearfiles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nuclearfiles.org/menu/timeline/1940/1945.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406133356/http://www.nuclearfiles.org/menu/timeline/1940/1945.htm |archivedate=2010-04-06 }}</ref>\n* July 16 &ndash; The [[Trinity (nuclear test)|Trinity]] test detonates the world's first [[atomic bomb]].\n* July 21 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: President [[Harry S. Truman]] approves the order for atomic bombs to be used against Japan.<ref name=\"nuclearfiles\" />\n* July 28 &ndash; A [[United States Army Air Forces|U.S. Army Air Forces]] [[B-25]] bomber crashes into the [[Empire State Building]], killing 14 people, including all on board.\n* July 30 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: The heavy cruiser {{USS|Indianapolis|CA-35|6}} is hit and sunk by torpedoes from the {{Jsub|I-58|1943|2}} in the [[Philippine Sea]]. Some 900 survivors jump into the sea and are adrift for up to four days. Nearly 600 die before help arrives. Captain [[Charles B. McVay III]] of the cruiser is later court-martialed and convicted.\n\n===August===\n[[File:Atomic cloud over Hiroshima.jpg|thumb|upright|August 6: [[Atomic bombing of Hiroshima]]]]\n* August 6 &ndash; [[World War II|WW II]]: [[Atomic bombing of Hiroshima]]: The United States drops an [[nuclear weapon|atomic bomb]] (nicknamed \"[[Little Boy]]\") on [[Hiroshima, Japan]], at 8:15&nbsp;a.m. (local time). This sent shockwaves throughout the world as the first atomic bomb used on civilians.\n* August 7 &ndash; President Harry Truman announces the successful bombing of Hiroshima with the [[nuclear weapon|atomic bomb]], while returning from the Potsdam Conference aboard the U.S. Navy heavy cruiser {{USS|Augusta|CA-31|6}} in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean.\n* August 8 &ndash; The [[United Nations Charter]] is ratified by the United States Senate, and this nation becomes the third one to join the new international organization.\n* August 9 &ndash; The United States drops an [[atomic bomb]] nicknamed \"[[Fat Man]]\" on  [[Nagasaki, Japan]], at 11:02&nbsp;a.m. (local time).\n* August 14 (August 15 in Japan) &ndash; Emperor [[Hirohito]] announces Japan's surrender on the radio. The United States calls this day [[V-J Day]] (Victory over Japan). This ends the period of [[Japanese expansionism]] and begins the period of [[Occupied Japan]].\n*August 17 &ndash; The United States and the [[U.S.S.R.]] split up the [[Korean Peninsula]] making [[North Korea]] and [[South Korea]]\n\n===September===\n* September 2 \n**[[World War II]] ends: The final official surrender of Japan is accepted by the Supreme Allied Commander, General [[Douglas MacArthur]], and [[Fleet admiral (United States)|Fleet Admiral]] [[Chester Nimitz]] for the United States, and delegates from Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, [[The Netherlands]], China, and others from a Japanese delegation led by [[Mamoru Shigemitsu]], on board the American battleship {{USS|Missouri|BB-63|6}} in Tokyo Bay (but in Japan August 14 is recognized as the day the [[Pacific War]] ended).\n**Japanese general [[Tomoyuki Yamashita]] surrenders to Filipino and American forces at [[Kiangan, Ifugao]].\n* September 5 \n** The Russian code clerk [[Igor Gouzenko]] comes forward with numerous documents implicating the Soviet Union in numerous spy rings in North America: both in the United States and in Canada.\n**[[Iva Toguri D'Aquino]], a Japanese-American suspected of being wartime radio propagandist \"[[Tokyo Rose]]\", is arrested in [[Yokohama]].\n* September 8 &ndash; American troops occupy southern [[Korea]], while the Soviet Union occupies the north, with the dividing line being the 38th parallel of latitude. This arrangement proves to be the indirect beginning of a divided [[Korea]].\n* September 9 &ndash; The first actual case of a (computer) [[Software bug|bug]] being found, is a [[moth]] lodged in a [[relay]] of a Harvard Mark II computer at the Naval Weapons Center in Dahlgren, Virginia.\n\n===October===\n* October 3\u201310 &ndash; The [[Detroit Tigers]] win the [[World Series]] against the [[Chicago Cubs]].\n* October 5 &ndash; A strike by the Set Decorator's Union in Hollywood results in a [[Hollywood Black Friday|riot]].\n* October 23 &ndash; [[Jackie Robinson]] signs a contract with the [[Montreal Royals]].\n* October 29 &ndash; At [[Gimbel's]] Department Store in New York City, the first [[ballpoint pen]]s go on sale at $12.50 each.\n\n===November===\n* November 15 &ndash; [[Harry S. Truman]], [[Clement Attlee]], and [[Mackenzie King]] call for a U.N. Atomic Energy Commission.<ref name=\"nuclearfiles\" />\n* November 16 &ndash; [[Cold War]]: The United States controversially imports 88 German scientists to help in the production of [[rocket]] technology.\n\n===December===\n* December 4 &ndash; By a vote of 65\u20137, the [[United States Senate]] approves the entry of the United States into the [[United Nations]].<ref name=\"NYT-OnThisDay\">{{citation |work=New York Times |url= http://learning.blogs.nytimes.com/on-this-day/ |title= On This Day |accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n* December 21 &ndash; General [[George S. Patton]] dies from injuries sustained in a car accident on December 9.\n\n===Undated===\n* The U.S. House of Representatives calls for unrestricted Jewish immigration to [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] in order to establish a Jewish commonwealth there.\n* The [[Berklee College of Music]] is founded in [[Boston]].\n* Russian-American physicist [[Vladimir Kosma Zworykin]] coauthors ''Electron Optics and the Electron Microscope''.\n\n==Ongoing==\n* [[World War II]], U.S. involvement (1941\u20131945)\n\n==Births==\n\n===January===\n[[File:Stephen Stills -- The Rides, Jun 2016.jpg|t